<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-297-201  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 297 201.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  Jan 23 1989 n522 p57(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Flash DACs grow in video. (digital-to-analog convertors)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Tatkow, Mark; Getchell, James.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Fast growing demands for high performance digital-to-analogconverters (DACs) and flash analog-to-digital converters (ADCs)are driven by, respectively, ever-higher-resolution color computerdisplays and high-technology testing, monitoring and researchequipment.andP;  Video DACs with speeds up to 500 MHz have appeared toprovide color displays with resolutions to 2,048 lines by 2,048pixels and clocks operating at rates up to 360 MHz.andO;High-performance systems require testing with parallel datasampling, timing accuracy of less than a nanosecond, low broadbandnoise, high-input bandwidth and control of timing system jitter.andO;Such systems typically include a timing system, triggering system,digital stimulus, analog sampling system and pixel clock card.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Market AnalysisTrendsDigital to Analog ConvertorsAnalog to Digital ConvertorsRequirements AnalysisTestingApplications.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraphtable.andO;Caption:   Pixel needs for various color monitor standards. (graph)Market potential for converters. (table)Video DAC specs. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>